Review Text:
Best Bagels I have ever tasted!!  A true New York-style bagel experience I was looking forward to in my visit to New York!                            Exceptional quality of the bagels with wide variety of cream cheese options and bagel options as well as generous portions!
I have tried several different bagels but the two I loved the most were the sesame bagel and the turkey bacon & cheddar cragel! The sesame bagel was crunchy on the outside with delicious taste of freshly roasted sesame and heavenly soft, and  fluffy in the inside. The turkey bacon and cheddar cragel was sooo delicious I kept eating even when I was full! I LOVE the texture AND taste. It is light, crunchy and soft all at the same time and has croissant taste to it but savory because of the cheddar cheese and the turkey bacon. Surly my new FAVORITE!
Also, if you stop by Bagel Point, you can‚Äôt leave without trying their home made Bagel Chips (crunchy and flavorful! Great with hummus or avocado dip) Furthermore, don‚Äôt forget their freshly in house made juices!! Especially the immune boost one! You can literally taste the freshness of each of the ingredients: the apples, carrots, oranges, kale and ginger!

Love their cheese texture! It‚Äôs whipped and fluffy yet VERY creamy!  They have great selection of both sweet and savory flavors! Lots of herbs and veggie options as well as fruits.

All in all, wide selection and variety of cream cheese options and  bagel flavors. They have everything from vegetarian options to meat lovers variety! From sweet to savory; Bagel Point has it all!! I would eat there every day without getting bored of it! 100% would recommend this place! great atmosphere, wonderful service, and overall amazing experience! I can‚Äôt wait to come back to NY just to eat here AGAIN! Bagel Point, please consider coming to MICHIGAN or start shipping !!! Specifically Ann Arbor MI (:

Review Text:
I've been to Montana's Meat Co countless times over the past six years, and they never disappoint with great service and delicious food. On a recent Friday, my friends and I visited this location and sat in the restaurant area. We were quickly greeted by Sage, our server, who made our experience even better. Sage was friendly, helpful, and had such a positive energy that really added to our meal.

I ordered the potato skins, a side salad, and the prime dip sandwich--everything was incredible! Honestly, you can't go wrong with anything on the menu. We've tried a variety of items over the years, from appetizers and wings to tenders, pastas, sandwiches, and more, and it's all been consistently amazing. It's never too loud inside, they even have a separate bar area for the smokers & gamblers which I appreciate that it's separate at times. Montana's is definitely one of my favorite spots in Vegas!

Keep up the great work!

Review Text:
I was very satisfied with my experience at this Pizza Inn.  Food was fresh, hot, and fast (and I saw service staff quality checking items that had been out for longer with frequency, and taking away unfinished items that I assume they felt were no longer fresh enough to serve to customers), as well as very good.  This Pizza Inn fully lived up to my expectations of this type of restaurant.  I only did the salad bar and pizza, so cannot speak to the pasta station.  For us and from a value perspective, we are never going to be able to eat enough for the buffet to be worth it from a quantity perspective, however; we find the value comes in being able to have such a large variety of items all in one meal.  As such, the price (I think around $15 for an adult) is well worth it.

The service staff were extremely nice and welcoming, especially the gentleman in the wheelchair who spoke to us while we were waiting for a seat.  My sole complaint, and seriously, this barely mattered to us, was that there was some pizza pieces on the floor next to us.  However, I feel like this was more due to the numerous young children at the table next to us rather than inattentiveness by the wait staff.  We dined on Saturday; it was busy.  These things happen.  If the trade off was one less person quality checking the food so that there was an additional on floor cleaning duty, I truly would not have taken that trade off.

Pizza buffets are unfortunately seemingly disappearing.  While I appreciate very much upscale pizza places and other types of restaurants, a pizza bar restaurant is a unique and, to me, nostalgic experience.  If you feel the same, this location should be on your list.

Review Text: We were in the Freehold area and figured we would knock another well known pizza place off the list.  We went around 4 on a Sunday.  It wasn't busy when we got there since it was sort of an off time, but definitely more packed when we left.  There is parking behind the building and free parking on Sunday evenings (maybe other times too, but we noticed for the time we were there).  Walking in the back there is an area for pickup of takeout orders.  If you walk straight ahead down the narrow hallway is up to the hostess station.  We were seated right away.  The restaurant is very long with different rooms.  We were taking all the way to the back where the bar was.  It definitely feels like you are stepping back in time in this restaurant.  The menu is somewhat limited, which sometimes I prefer.  We knew we were going to get pizza but was unsure of which kind.  We grabbed a couple waters and some sodas and perused the menu a bit.  I was thinking based on seeing other patrons pizzas, it would be similar to Vic's in Bradley Beach.  We realized we are not HUGE fans of thin crust pizza but was still willing to try.  We decided on the Vodka Sauce pizza.  It came out pretty fast.  It was HOT so we let it cool a bit.  It was definitely thin crust.  Crispy but not overly crispy.  We are very happy we got it was the vodka sauce as it gave it a little dimension.  It was good.  Crispy, gooey enough cheese, and the right amount of sauce.  Service was very good and was happy to try this place.  We saw some of the other people's meals which also looked good! Next time we would try one of the Italian dishes.

It's sad to say but Huber's has lost its mojo. In the 90s, Hubers had class, had style, had that certain je ne sais quoi. I took my parents there for Thanksgiving dinner when it wasn't even Thanksgiving.  The server would mesmerize us, making Spanish Coffees table-side with dramatic flare.  But that was yesteryear.  

On a recent visit I was on my own, so I sat at the bar.  The place was almost empty with maybe three tables and a group of three at the other end of the bar.  After several minutes ticked by with no bartender, the host came over and brought me a glass of water.  Then I sat there with my water for several more minutes before the bartender finally resurfaced and absently poured me a glass of water, not noticing that I already had one until she almost put her glass on top of mine.  The rest of the evening didn't go much better.  She seemed more intent on replenishing her coffee tray and putting away the clean glassware from the dishwasher than checking on me.  When I finished my salad, my empty plate sat on the bar for a good long while.  I ordered a salad because I was looking forward to a slice of pumpkin pie.  At least the pie is still good.

Review Text:
I usually don't write negative reviews, but my recent experience at Arya Steakhouse was so frustrating, I felt compelled to share. The food was decent, but the billing practices here are downright infuriating.

First off, they added a mandatory 20% tip to the bill, which I understand at some places, but what really got me was that they charged extra tax on the tip itself. This is not only unreasonable, but it feels like a total rip-off. It's the kind of thing that leaves a bad taste in your mouth, even if the meal itself was fine.

As if that wasn't enough, there was also a 4% "living wage" surcharge added on top. They didn't really explain this in advance, so it came as an unpleasant surprise when the check arrived. Between the tip, the extra tax on the tip, and the surcharge, it felt like they were padding the bill at every turn. 

For a place that's supposed to offer a nice dining experience, this feels like a cash grab. I get that tipping culture is a thing, but these hidden fees are just too much. I won't be coming back, and I wouldn't recommend this place to anyone who values transparency in pricing.

Review Text:
I am sharing this mainly for any potential black patrons.  We experienced blatant racism when attempting to dine there on Saturday December 7, 2024.  An elderly friend of the family we were eating with arrived at the restaurant first.  He attempted to request a table in the main dining room for our party. He was told that there was no availability in the main dining room and there wouldn't be any that evening. He was told that he could have a table at a high top. The high top tables are not conducive for older guests and tend to be uncomfortable. When I arrive he tells me and the rest of our party what they told him.  I proceed to go on Open Table to verify that what he was told was actually true.  If you know how Open Table works, they have access to the resraurants table management system. It is how they update information in real time.  Open table shows that the restaurant has multiple openings for seating for four in the main dining room over the next hour.  Open table gives you the choice between the main dining room and their high tops.  When I show the hostess Gaby this, she tried to tell me that the information in Open Table is wrong and they really don't have any seating.  The lie was so bad and so comical that she would have been better off just telling the truth.  Anyone can do a search to see how open table works with their restaurants table management systems and what she described was a lie.  My recommendation for any black patrons who see this is not to give them your money, they clearly don't want to serve us so give them what they want. No need to fight and argue to give them money.

I added the Open Table screen shot for reference.

Review Text: We've dined at Bastille many times and have had wonderful experiences there. This time, Bastille missed the mark. Bastille is not inexpensive and when we choose to go there, there is an expectation for good food and good service. I'll start with the service, our server took our order very professionally, and then things went down hill. I ordered the Entrecote, and received a beef filet, I decided to stay with the fillet as all three others in my party had received their food. The beef fillet was not very good and tough. I had to ask for a steak knife as she brought me a butter knife in a very celebratory fashion and presentation, I was quite surprised by that as she knew I needed an additional knife, but did not bring a steak knife.  Dinner continued and the atmosphere was lovely as it always is. For desert I requested a cheese tray. When it arrived, it was simply placed on our table with no explanation of what the cheeses were. The region, goat vs cow milk, and other details are what is fairly standard when serving cheese trays. This was at the end of our meal and we had no silverware on the table as it had been cleared by the busing staff. I had to get my server's attention to have a knife brought to the table and then asked her about the cheeses. To my horror, she did not know what they were and  left to find out what they were serving. This is unacceptable for a restaurant where we spend $250.00 for two of us. There were other miscues, which some can be expected from time to time, but I'll stop there. This restaurant can, and has done better. We may or may not give them another shot as there several French restaurants in walking distance of our home in Old Town.

Review Text: We were greeted pretty promptly when we arrived for my birthday dinner, just my husband, myself and our son. We were given a booth on the Lindbergh side which was otherwise empty at the time, but a couple other tables were soon filled.  The decor in the main area seemed very Gulf coast/Margaritaville-esque which works!  The booth area we were in had had some folks go wild with a Sharpie, totally filled with drawings and writing, including requests for VenMo gifts, which was a bit weird. Our waitress was sweet, friendly and swift and brought us complimentary seafood bread which was tasty!  I ordered a half pound of king crab legs and a half pound boiled shrimp.  I chose the "traditional" boil and thought it was a little bland, but the crab was sweet and delicious with just some drawn butter and the cocktail sauce was perfectly horseradish-y for the shrimp.  My husband had Cajun seasoned boil with shrimp, crawfish and sausage.  It was huge and he really enjoyed it.  Our picky son had chicken nuggets that looked crispy and he actually did eat them, so fair enough. The bathrooms were clean, too.  Oh, and you should definitely make use of the bib and gloves provided with your seafood boil!  Only thing that would have been helpful would be some wet wipes, but hubby was able to clean up enough with napkins to visit the men's room for a full handwashing before we hit the road.
